              <p class="oral-exchange__q">{ex.q}</p>
              {ex.rows.map((row) => (
                <div class="oral-exchange__row">
                  <span class="oral-exchange__badge">{row.stage}</span>
                  <div>
                    <span class="oral-exchange__stage">{row.label}</span>
                    <p class="oral-exchange__text">{row.text}</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              ))}
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p class="oral-exchange__note">Each Link is deliberately forward-looking &mdash; it leaves the examiner something to respond to, which is how a discussion is sustained rather than restarted question by question.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="oral-sets">
        <span class="oral-sets__label">The four practice sets</span>
        <div class="oral-sets__chips">
          {oralSets.map((s, i) => (
            <span class="oral-sets__chip"><strong>Set {i + 1}</strong> {s}</span>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="oral-source">From the A-Worthy <strong>PEEL Model Answer Scheme</strong> (Syllabus 1184): 4 practice sets &middot; 4 planned-response models &middot; 24 spoken-interaction models &middot; SEAB band descriptors reproduced verbatim. Accompanies the Video-Based Oral Practice Pack used in lessons.</p>

      <div class="oral-tip">
        <span class="oral-tip__tag">Common mistake</span>
        <p>Avoid answering only at the level of the video. Weak responses describe what the participants are doing; strong ones explain why the activity has lasting value beyond the clip &mdash; and reciting a model answer word for word sounds unnatural, so adapt the ideas to the exact stimulus shown.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

